netsquid.util.constrainedmap

Classes to constrain a value or variable within a mapping. For example to check for type, make it mutable or set some bounds.

Used in the Component class to restrict users to input incorrect values or modify them during a run

class netsquid.util.constrainedmap.ConstrainedMap(data=None, mutability=None, types=None, value_constraints=None, global_constraints=None)

Bases: Mapping

A mapping used for storing key-value pairs subject to constraints.

Functions similarly to a dict except that items can only be set if they are already present and, where applicable, are mutable, have the correct type, and pass any set constraints.

Parameters:

  • data (dict or None, optional) – Key-value pairs to initialize map with. None if map is empty.

  • mutability (dict or None, optional) – Whether each key is mutable.

  • types (dict or None, optional) – Type of each key. None indicates no fixed type.

  • value_constraints (dict or None, optional) – ValueConstraints for each key. None indicates no extra constraints

  • global_constraints (list, optional) – ValueConstraints that act on all keys.

get_type(key)

tuple of type or None: get the type(s) of item corresponding to a key.

get_mutable(key)

bool: get whether the item corresponding to a key is mutable.

get_global_constraints()

list of ValueConstraint: get the global constraints of this map

get_constraints(key)

list of ValueConstraint: get the list of constraints of this key

internal_add(key, value=None, mutable=True, value_type=None, value_constraints=None)

Add an item to this mapping.

This is an internal method that is not intended to be called by users of this mapping.

Parameters:

  • key (hashable) – Key of item.

  • value (Any) – Value of item.

  • mutable (bool, optional) – Whether item is mutable.

  • value_type (type, tuple of type or None, optional) – Type of item or None if no type.

  • value_constraints (ValueConstraint or list of ~netsquid.util.constrainedmap.ValueConstraint , optional) – Constraint check such as type and bounds

Raises:

KeyError – If the key already exists in the mapping.

internal_del(key)

Remove an item from the mapping.

This is an internal method that is not intended to be called by users of this mapping.

Parameters:

key (str) – Key of item.

filter_by_type(value_type)

Get the keys of this map which values are of the given type

Parameters:

value_type (type) – type or class of items to filter the mapping on

Returns:

A view of this constrained map containing only key value pairs of the given type.

Return type:

ConstrainedMapView

Notes

The returned object is immutable; changing the map doesn’t change the returned object.

class netsquid.util.constrainedmap.ConstrainedMapView(constrained_map, constraints)

Bases: Mapping

Mapping that filters out values of a dict or constrained map.

When iterating over this view or getting items from this view it will filter out the items that do not pass the constraints.

Parameters:

  • constrained_map (ConstrainedMap) – Constrained map to filter based on constraints.

  • constraints (list of ValueConstraint) – The constraints to filter on.

Example

>>> from netsquid.util.constrainedmap import (ConstrainedMap,
...                                           ConstrainedMapView,
...                                           ValueConstraint)
...
>>> cm = ConstrainedMap({"a": 4, "b":-5, "c": 1000, "d": 42})
>>> map_view = ConstrainedMapView(cm, [ValueConstraint(lambda x: x > 0),
...                                    ValueConstraint(lambda x : x < 100)])
>>> len(map_view)
2
>>> print(map_view)
ConstrainedMapView({'a': 4, 'd': 42})
>>> for i in map_view:
...     print(i)
a
d
>>> "a" in map_view
True
>>> "b" in map_view
False
>>> cm["b"] = 34
>>> "b" in map_view
True
>>> map_view["b"]
34
>>> for k, v in map_view.items():
...     print(k, v)
a 4
b 34
d 42
>>> print([k for k in map_view.keys()])
['a', 'b', 'd']
>>> print([v for v in map_view.values()])
[4, 34, 42]
property map

constrained map this is a view of.

Type:

ConstrainedMap

class netsquid.util.constrainedmap.ValueConstraint(constraint_function, error_message=None, error_type=None)

Bases: object

An object used by constrained maps to set constraints for its values.

Values that are changed on runtime (if they are mutable) should still be valid. By using a list of value constraints in a ConstrainedMap these values can be validated.

Parameters:

  • constraint_function (callable) – A lambda, method, function or any other callable with 1 argument that should return True if the value passes the constraint test

  • error_message (str, optional) – Error message to show when value is not valid

  • error_type (Exception, optional) – Exception to raise when value is not valid, default is a ValueError

check(value, throw_error=True)

Checks if value passes the constraint, if not raises the specified error.

Parameters:

  • value (object) – object to check the constraints on

  • throw_error (bool, optional) – whether an error should be thrown (true) or False should be returned. Default True

Returns:

True if value passes the constraint check False if it does not pass and throw_error is False

Return type:

bool

constr_not(error_message=None, error_type=None)

Negates the current constraint.

Parameters:

  • error_message (str, optional) – Error message to show when value is not valid, None will keep error message of self

  • error_type (Exception, optional) – Exception to raise when value is not valid, default is error of self

Returns:

A new ValueConstraint that passes value if and only if self would not pass the value

Return type:

ValueConstraint

constr_and(other)

Combines two constraints, where both should be true :Parameters: other (ValueConstraint) – constraint to combine this constraint with

Returns:

A new ValueConstraint that passes value if both constraints are true

Return type:

ValueConstraint

Notes

Obsolete, can also pass a list of ValueConstraints into the map, or rewrite the value constraint
